/**
 Express.js â€“ express.Router() (Easy & Real-world Explanation)

--------------------------------------------------
ðŸ”¹ Router kya hota hai? (Simple words me)

- express.Router() ek mini express app jaisa hota hai
- Iska use routes ko alagâ€“alag file me todne ke liye hota hai
- Taaki code clean, readable aur manageable rahe

ðŸ‘‰ Simple line me:
Router ka use karke hum "routes ko group" kar dete hain

--------------------------------------------------
ðŸ”¹ Router ke bina problem kya hoti hai? (IMPORTANT)

Agar router use nahi karte, to:
- Saare routes ek hi file (server.js / app.js) me aa jate hain
- File bahut lambi ho jati hai
- Samajhna mushkil ho jata hai
- Maintain karna hard ho jata hai
- Real-world projects me ye BAD PRACTICE hai

--------------------------------------------------
ðŸ”¹ Router ke bina example (Problem)

import express from "express";
const app = express();

app.get("/api/users", (req, res) => {
  res.send("Get all users");
});

app.post("/api/users", (req, res) => {
  res.send("Create user");
});

app.get("/api/products", (req, res) => {
  res.send("Get all products");
});

app.post("/api/products", (req, res) => {
  res.send("Create product");
});

app.listen(3000);

âŒ Problem:
- Users aur Products ke routes mix ho gaye
- Jaise-jaise app badhega, file aur gandi hoti jayegi
- Kisi ek feature ke routes dhoondhna mushkil ho jayega

--------------------------------------------------
ðŸ”¹ Router ke bina dry run (Samajhne ke liye)

Request:
GET /api/users

Flow:
1) Express server.js file ko top se check karega
2) Pehle matching route milega
3) app.get("/api/users") execute ho jayega
4) Response send ho jayega

ðŸ‘‰ Chal to raha hai, lekin structure kharab hai

--------------------------------------------------
ðŸ”¹ Router use karne ka idea (Solution)

- Users ke routes â†’ users.routes.js
- Products ke routes â†’ products.routes.js
- Main file sirf router ko mount karegi

--------------------------------------------------
ðŸ”¹ Router ke saath example (Clean & Professional)

users.routes.js
----------------
import express from "express";
const router = express.Router();

router.get("/", (req, res) => {
  res.send("Get all users");
});

router.post("/", (req, res) => {
  res.send("Create user");
});

export default router;

--------------------------------------------------

products.routes.js
------------------
import express from "express";
const router = express.Router();

router.get("/", (req, res) => {
  res.send("Get all products");
});

router.post("/", (req, res) => {
  res.send("Create product");
});

export default router;

--------------------------------------------------

server.js
---------
import express from "express";
import userRouter from "./users.routes.js";
import productRouter from "./products.routes.js";

const app = express();

app.use("/api/users", userRouter);
app.use("/api/products", productRouter);

app.listen(3000);

--------------------------------------------------
ðŸ”¹ Router ke saath dry run (IMPORTANT)

Request:
GET /api/users

Flow:
1) Express server.js me request receive karega
2) app.use("/api/users", userRouter) match hoga
3) Control userRouter ko de diya jayega
4) Router ke andar "/" path check hoga
5) router.get("/") match ho jayega
6) Response send ho jayega

Output:
Get all users

--------------------------------------------------
ðŸ”¹ Router ke saath path ka magic (IMPORTANT)

server.js:
app.use("/api/users", userRouter);

users.routes.js:
router.get("/", handler);

ðŸ‘‰ Actual URL ban jata hai:
GET /api/users

Isliye router file me "/api/users" likhne ki zaroorat nahi hoti

--------------------------------------------------
ðŸ”¹ Router se kya problem solve hoti hai?

âœ… Code clean ho jata hai  
âœ… Har feature ke routes alag ho jate hain  
âœ… Large project manageable ho jata hai  
âœ… Team work easy ho jata hai  
âœ… Debugging easy ho jati hai  

--------------------------------------------------
ðŸ”¹ Router + middleware (Real-world use)

Example:
router.use(authMiddleware);

Iska matlab:
- Is router ke saare routes pe auth middleware lagega
- Baar-baar likhne ki zaroorat nahi

--------------------------------------------------
ðŸ”¹ Interview GOLD line

express.Router() ek modular routing system provide karta hai
jisse routes ko logically separate karke clean aur scalable
Express.js applications banayi ja sakti hain.

--------------------------------------------------
 Final One-Line Conclusion

Router ke bina app chal sakti hai,
lekin router ke saath app professional, scalable
aur real-world ready banti hai.
